Patch Set 3:> > (1 comment) > > > > So I did an initial review of the patch and I think the general > > concept is ok but I'm still not sure about some of the details. > > > > Mainly the use of -1 as special column index and having special > > cases for it everywhere. > > > > I'm not sure if we should not instead switch to a solution that > has > > a valid ScAttrArray for any ScColumn and if there is not yet a > > ScColumn inside of the ScTable we query the ScAttrArray stored in > > ScTable. I need to read more and talk to you, Eike and Kohei to > see > > what is the best solution. >  > Thanks for the review. >  > The ScAttrArray object (aNextColAttrArray) in the ScTable has its > nCol member set to -1 to indicate that it represents all > unallocated columns. The check nCol == -1 in ScAttrArray methods is > to prevent making calls to pDocument methods like InvalidateTextWidth() > from aNextColAttrArray as it requires a valid/existing Column. >  > The special cases in the ScAttrArray methods are in fact for the > case of default formatting where nCount == 0 and pData == nullptr.But do we actually call these methods for the default formatting? As far as I read the code the default formatting is stored in the ScTable instance. If these methods are supposed to be never called for the default formatting I think an assert is the better solution.Sorry that it currently takes me a bit longer to review patches. I'm quite busy with my thesis and can not afford to spend too much time on LibreOffice.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1(7 comments)So.. with the third attempt to review I finally managed to wrap my head around this.. ;-)I think having the aNextColAttrArray for unallocated columns at ScTable is a good approach. Same as Markus I'm not very fond of the spurious nCol!=-1 checks sprinkled over, but I also don't have a better solution. Calling any document content related functions for the unallocated column clearly must not happen.Overall I'm impressed, you seem to have dug deeply into this.I have some inline comments about some minor changes. Once these are done, do you think this would be ready to be added for 5.3?

Patch Set 3:> I think having the aNextColAttrArray for unallocated columns at > ScTable is a good approach. Same as Markus I'm not very fond of the > spurious nCol!=-1 checks sprinkled over, but I also don't have a > better solution. Calling any document content related functions for > the unallocated column clearly must not happen.Hi EikeThanks a lot for the review. Just to clarify regarding the nCol != -1 check, we need to let methods like Reset(), SetPatternArea(), ApplyStyleArea() to be called for the aNextColAttrArray but *without* changing any document content. An alternative to nCol != -1 checks is that we can have a default parameter or data member called bUnallocated with default value = false for all such methods and use that instead of (nCol != -1) when calling from aNextColAttrArray. Would that be better at least in terms of readability of the code ?In the meantime I will fix the other issues as per your comments. Thanks.

Patch Set 1:> > However I decided against it, since reading configuration on > every repaint brings some performance penalty >  > I see, just wondered if the performance penalty is really severe or > not. I didn't observe any slowdown myself, but that doesn't mean that other people wouldn't, who knows what they do with their office :) e.g. this blogpost explains why are frequent configuration readings a bad idea: https://mmohrhard.wordpress.com/2015/10/07/short-update-about-the-performance-testing/ > What we want then would be to derive utl::ConfigurationListener and > provide a suitable ConfigurationChanged( ::utl::ConfigurationBroadcaster*, > sal_uInt32 ), > as in Calc's ScModule (ScModule::ConfigurationChanged() in > sc/source/ui/app/scmod.cxx) > and Writer's SwModule (SwModule::ConfigurationChanged in > sw/source/uibase/app/apphdl.cxx), etc. > Right?Aye, that's exactly what I meant :)

Patch Set 2:FWIW, given enough time, I would like to get rid of these MS-DOC style end-of-cell and end-of-row markers in dmapper, let dmapper work with the OOXML table model with its explicit starts and ends (instead of gluing similar rows together), and move all the create-table-from-similar-rows heuristics from dmapper to rtftok, which still needs it.It bothers me a bit that in the OOXML case we drop this table start/end information in the tokenizer, then in dmapper we spend time reconstructing it again. But it's not a trivial change, and it has been always like this, so not urgent... :-)The fact that in RTF it's OK to specify table properties after the contents of the table, while OOXML specifies it before (and because of this, the RTF tokenizer has to buffer the table contents) is just a cherry on the "cake".

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1(4 comments)Looks good so far, but there is small problem with default creation:As soon as you override the CreateDefaultObject method, what happens is that SwFEShell::CreateDefaultShape is never called for all SIDs that use ConstRectangle. So:1. SwFEShell::CreateDefaultShape has code that previously handled line creation (OBJ_LINE case), and now it becomes unused.2. Some SIDs aren't properly handled in the new CreateDefaultObject, so e.g. if you create a textbox, it created outside the page, then "jumps" into its place.We have now 2 options:1. Implement support for all ConstRectangle based SIDs into CreateDefaultObject, and remove the unused code from SwFEShell::CreateDefaultShape.2. Not override CreateDefaultObject, and instead implement everything in SwFEShell::CreateDefaultShape.

Patch Set 5:Looks great, but there were some bugs and tweaks that are needed.Default should be the first entry in the submenu menu.If set to notebookbar, restarting LO wont show notebookbar and changing it to another mode and then back to notebookbar wont make it appear.If notebookbar is enabled, .uno:AvailableToolbars should be disabled.If notebookbar isnt enabled, .uno:Notebookbar should be disabled.For default mode, if the sidebar is opened/closed/only showing the 'show' arrow button, it should be opened only showing the tab bars (what it looks like when you open writer with a cleared profile).For single toolbar mode, the sidebar should be enabled but collapsed only showing the 'show' arrow button, the toolbar icons need to be changed to small if they are set to automatic and the icon style should be changed to sifr if set to automatic. this means that before the activation of single toolbar mode, the icon size and style needs to be preserved in the user profile for non-single toolbar mode, as well as saving it for when exiting single toolbar mode so it can be restored when returning to single toolbar mode. In this mode, all contextual toolbar should be disabled (https://bugs.documentfoundation.org/show_bug.cgi?id=92218#c13).For sidebar mode, the sidbear should be fully opened whatever state it is in and set to the properties tab.For notebookbar mode, the sidebar should be collapsed to show the 'show' arrrow button, similar to single toolbar mode.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1Love it - thanks for the swamp draining Markus ! =) I guess my lingering concern is what happens when we have SEH enabled code that catches a SEGV vs. normal code - does that mean we get various exceptions thrown out of eg. OGL drivers that are compiled with this option (?) etc. anyhow - moving closer to the Linux case sounds like a good idea to me for window stability =)Thanks.

Patch Set 2:> Love it - thanks for the swamp draining Markus ! =) I guess my > lingering concern is what happens when we have SEH enabled code > that catches a SEGV vs. normal code - does that mean we get various > exceptions thrown out of eg. OGL drivers that are compiled with > this option (?) etc. anyhow - moving closer to the Linux case > sounds like a good idea to me for window stability =) >  > Thanks.So EHs only affects whether we catch the SEH or not. It does not affect how other code handles it. Of course if we get a lot of SEH excepions from outside of our control that are currently caught in one of the catch all handlers we are going to crash a lot.EHs has basically two effects on the code. catch(...) will not catch SEH exceptions and there is no stack nwinding and destructor calls going to be for SEH exceptions.I think both are fine in our code. The case that some external part is handling SEH with EHa should not concern us as if we get a SEH from that cod ewe will just crash and if that code handles it we are not going to see it anyway.

Patch Set 1:> What is the actual purpose of this?The formula bar in LOK case is not tiled rendered, so we cannot interact with theformula bar directly. In this case, we need a way so that client applicationscan simulate a formula bar.> Why not update dependent formula cells, conditional formatting and so on?We do not want to update dependent formula cells with each keystroke when theuser is still writing his/her input into the formula bar because these areintermediate values. It could be an incomplete formula or an invalid value whichwould result in throwing error for all dependent cells. We only want to updatethese dependent cells in some particular condition, say pressing enter, informula bar. Hence the distinction in this UNO command now, so that when theuser is just typing, we don't commit the contents to the cell.I tried looking for other ways to accomplish this, but this approach made mostsense to me. Surely, if you have any suggestions, please let me know :-)> What should happen if one enters a numeric value / date / formula?The cell should go in edit mode with each keystroke in formula bar updating itscontents but not commit till we press enter(by not specifying DontCommit param).

Patch Set 2:> The formula bar in LOK case is not tiled rendered, so we cannot > interact with the > formula bar directly. In this case, we need a way so that client > applications > can simulate a formula bar. > We do not want to update dependent formula cells with each > keystroke when the > user is still writing his/her input into the formula bar because > these are > intermediate values.Thanks for explaining. Makes sense.

Patch Set 2:Hi Faruk,Thanks for working on this, it looks awesome, except I have few comments that I think should be taken care of before we merge this. What do you think ?1. tpstatus label is obscured; not clearly visible. Maybe better if we add a background below this label, or something to make it visible clearly ?2. It should be possible to close the dialog when user clicks somewhere else. Currently, only way to close the dialog is to hit again on the toolbar button.3. I think we should limit the dimensions of table user can create with this new toolbar button just like we do in desktop, because if we don't it would stick to the mouse movements and user will have a hard time to find an empty space to close the dialog button. This is pretty annoying from user POV, I think.4. I noticed that the state of this new toolbar button doesn't get reset whenever user manages to close the dialog. So for eg: if user closed the dialog with table dimensions 12 x 12 selected, the next time he opens it, it would still be at 12 x 12. The state should be reset everytime dialog is closed.5. Currently, user has to move his mouse slowly to select desired dimensions. If he moves the mouse little faster, the dialog doesn't notice that.6. You have limited the width of dialog unlike its height. I think you intend to limit the number of columns user can choose here (?), _but_ if user moves his mouse back and forth near the right edge, more number of columns gets added to the same width increasing the number of cells per row - density - which makes the grid a mess. Can we somehow avoid that ? Also as pointed out in (3) limiting number of rows makes sense here.Besides these, I found a missing '+' (see inline comments which makes me suspect this is not the version you have in your local box since this version doesn't work out of the box unless someone changes code himself - is it ?)

Patch Set 3:> Let me explain in more detail... >  > It is common in code to use a clever trick to get more informative > text into the message from a failed assert(). For instance, one > could have (this a generic example, not from LibreOffice): >  > assert(nFoo > 0 && "We should have at least one foo widget"); >  > with the intent being that in case nFoo is <= 0, instead of the > message: >  > Assertion failed: nFoo > 0 >  > one would get this message, with a longer explanation: >  > Assertion failed: nFoo > 0 && "We should have at least one foo > widget" >  > In the code lines here, the string literal contains what is > essentially identical to the expression on the left side of the && > operator, so it does not give any additional information.ohh, now i understand. Actually i never used assert in any of my programming projects. I'm a 1-2 yr amatuer C++ programmer. Whatever the result may be, open source coding is always a great learning experience. Thanks for such a great explanation. I would update all of my patches tommorow morning.

Patch Set 6:Thank you for your comments, I will look into them and correct the code where possible.In general:-I switched from vector< double > to array of doubles in an attempt to improve performance; but didn't try to measure the difference; I haven't looked into leaks and leak-protection, so I may switch them back to vector.-Some vectors were maintained as they are sorted or have to passed as vector to existing functions.-I now have 8 new functions, of which Excel doesn't have 3 (the multiplicative method, which is more realistic and IMHO of more use when forecasting). These 3 functions don't have an _xlfn prefix in OOXML as they don't exist there. I haven't fully checked yet if all entries in formulabase.cxx and xlformula.cxx are correct here.-My main efforts so far have been to get the functions working as they should (and changing constraints where MS Excel preaches them but does _not_ apply them).I want to change one last constraint (the time(X)-interval needs to be constant, but in case of dates an interval of months (28 to 31 days) is accepted by Excel. I have to find out how much deviation is accepted by Excel and how to incorporate this in the code, with interpolation in forecasts etc..Then I want to do a lot of numerical comparisons between Calc and Excel - where possible.Then I need to make a unit test; simple no-difference check with Excel is not possible as it is a forecast and the result depends on the exact method and sometimes random numbers.Then I want to go through the code again with a toothbrush.Then I want to prepare help-text (for someone else to put into the repository).And then my draft could become a real submission.We'll be in 2016 be then, it's a huge job - for me, at least ;)

Patch Set 4:Hmm. That will most likely hurt us later but well we can deal with it then.I had chats with Kohei and Eike and I think the solution that seems to be acceptable to all of us is to use a std::vector<ScColumn*> or std::vector<std::unique_ptr<ScColumn>> with the additional requirement that there are no nullptr entries.This provides us with some benefits compared to the version without the additional requirement and the version based on std::vector<ScColumn>. We don't need to check every entry while iterating through columns (just compare once against std::vector::size) and we don't need to worry that pointers to ScColumn instances become invalid when we insert or remove a column. I hope this helps you for the rest of the work.

Patch Set 1:Thank you for your valuable feedback. As per my understanding, we cannot tell with certainty if the last entry is a cell name or not without invoking the formula engine. We cannot use a flag to keep track of the last entry because it could have been typed in, so there won't be a trigger for the flag.   The current solution does not cover all situations (for example, if the last letter is a space character), but I think it would cover the most common use cases, without having to invoke formula engine  with every change.If you think the formula is getting parsed with each change already, or if you think it won't be much of an overhead, then if you could give me some pointers, I could use that in the solution.Thanks

Patch Set 1:> Thank you for your valuable feedback. As per my understanding, we > cannot tell with certainty if the last entry is a cell name or not > without invoking the formula engine. We cannot use a flag to keep > track of the last entry because it could have been typed in, so > there won't be a trigger for the flag.IMHO that isn't needed. > The current solution does not cover all situations (for example, if > the last letter is a space character), but I think it would cover > the most common use cases, without having to invoke formula engine  > with every change.It already fails if the Excel R1C1 reference style is activated, becausethen references end with ']'.Instead of using an "allowed characters" comparison I'd use a "forbiddencharacters" comparison. There are likely only two cases we want tocover, namely the first parameter of a function that takes more than oneparameters (otherwise the user would not use Ctrl+Click for severalreferences) and the case where a separator is already present, i.e. wasmanually typed. This limits it to the characters '(' and ',' (rathercSep separator) that if present as last characters (maybe ignoringtrailing spaces) lead to the separator not having to be added.

You need to update to a git checkout that ncludes the pushed patch already. One solution to avoid long recompile times is to have a separate push tree + charry-picking the commit from current master. Then only add the new commit to the push tree (which already contains the pushed commit) and push to gerrit for review.Gerrit complained that you tried to push a patch that has been merged already to gerrit review. Patch Set 1:This seems a ridiculous discussion to me ;-) doer decides is a vital meritocratic principle =) quibbling adds little value it seems to me.Beyond that - there is nothing simple about APU hardware; we have both GPU and CPU compute resources with things akin to threads in them. Cores is also an horribly misleading term in a SMT world. There are even pending law-suits around "what is a core" - how many resources can be shared etc. There is no "obvious" answer to this question.What we are returning is: the result of std::thread::hardware_concurrency() - we can provide a hyper-descriptive label for this: but then we'll be sending a truck-load of these across the net for years, and there is only so much space in Help->About =)What is in the patch has the merit of brevity; if someone wants to change it to CPU Threads Hardware Concurency - to follow STL or whatever, they are welcome to - preferably in a separate, follow-up patch - that also line-wraps this for Help->About.

Patch Set 4:Michael, many thanks for the review. I have fixed the name, also improved the patch to limit GetObject only at repeated image loading/overloading, and pushed to the master. (The  repeated image loading could be a result of the repaint triggered by the second call of GetObject - after the successful asynchronous loading of an image.)

Patch Set 6:> FnHashSet ? - what is the function ? surely a better, more descriptive type name is possibleI have renamed as AsyncLoads in the patch set 6.> Also - I suggested a much clearer name for this hash; but ... this is not it =)I had already changed the member variable name, but you checked an older patch set (patch set 3 instead of the last 5 at that time). > Why have this variable rather than using an empty-hash (and hence no lookup match) ?I have already removed that code in the patch set 6.> Why are we erasing here ? this seems inexplicable to me; I commented on it before; you seem to have responded to the comment - but this is not clear.> If the load of this filename is in-progress - then we prematurely remove it from being in-progress here, before it is loaded (right?) - why ?We want to skip only one LoadFile_Impl() call to avoid immediate paint and recursive image loadings. This skipped LoadFile_Impl() call is the last for the object, when the image loading is finished (see backtrace "Second LoadFile_Impl() call of an asynchronous image loading" in the Bug 95614).Or this call can be the first LoadFile_Impl() call of an other SvFileObject loading the same picture, so we won't start that image loading immediately.This stops freezing with linked images and recent scheduler.Many thanks for the review.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1Seems reasonable enough I guess - I would name the member variable something sensible; m_aAsyncLoadsInProgress.I'm also really unclear why we erase the item from the hash if it is already there - when requesting the image [ that seems ... odd ] Surely we want to erase that when the async loading has completed (whether it succeeded or failed) - rather than when the 2nd image request is made (what about a 3rd request ?).Anyhow - conceptually loading the same graphic twice does indeed look bogus & good to stop; though whether this is truly the root cause of the freeze is unclear to me =)Thanks.

Patch Set 4:> > RGB happens to be defined by wingdi.h and leaks from multiple > > places. This was the easiest/simplest fix; to undef it where it > > conflicts. For other cases it was enough to undef them in > postwin.h > > and make sure it's called after including windows headers. >  > But wouldn't it be better to handle undef'ing RGB in postwin.h, and > make sure any include of wingdi.h is wrapped in prewin/postwin.h? I tried that. And can give it another try. But it would require a much bigger change, obviously. The main problem is that wingdi.h is actually included from other windows headers too. So we can't fully control when it's included. But can give it another shot and narrow it down further. In fact, I spent hours trying to find what file includes the conflicting values to create this patch. > The current fix allows workdir/CustomTarget/officecfg/registry/officecfg/Office/Common.hxx > to be included, but if a source file happens to first include that > officecfg/Office/Common.hxx, then include wingdi.h, and later wants > to acutally use the struct RGB from Common.hxx, it still runs into > a problem.Well, that would be be a problem _only_ if wingdi.h was already included _before_ Office/Common.h, and in that case the build would fail because the macro would conflict with the declaration of RGB (my patch avoids this situation).However, if wingdi.h was _not_ included at the point of #undef RGB, then nothing bad would happen if it is included afterwards. Unless I missed something, I don't see how there would still be a problem, as wingdi.h will define RGB without issue.I should add that I hated this particular line of my patch. I share your view that it's best avoided altogether. But I couldn't find a better solution. Will try again though.

Patch Set 4:I wish we had aw080 already, all SdrObjects fully transformable, mirroring preserved...The current Rectangle unfortunately allows such bad/inconsistent states (left() > right()), thats why justify is needed (and why B2DRange is better, this can not happen). The Rectangle is *not* the place to keep such information. It's place is at the model (the SdrObject). See ::TRGetBaseGeometry implementations where the mirroring is coming from - e.g in SdrObjCustomShape it *is* a model member (X and Y).Currently - except for the SdrObjCustomShape and SdrGrafObj - the mirrored states are not preserved - the mirroring is geometrically *executed* on the existing geometry, that's it (aw080 changes this).You can see this sad truth e.g. at the graphic object - insert one in Draw/Impress and add text. Hor mirror does not change the text at all, vertical mirror uses a 180 deg rotation, *not* a true vert mirroring.This only does not come to more attention due to the fact that nearly all shapes are CustomShapes nowadays...Do not forget: mirror in X and Y equals a 180 deg rotation (can be seen/proved looking at the corrresponding homogen matrix)

Patch Set 1:To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous commit. Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new thread. Hope this helps!

Patch Set 1:> To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving > the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes > it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then > you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous > commit.Git commit --amend is a much easier way to do that.iow checkout your gerrit patchdo the modificationscommit them using --amendgit push origin HEAD:refs/for/master Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed > commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new > thread. Hope this helps!

Patch Set 3:Thank you for your review.I think that DECODE_WITH_CHARSET is better than DECODE_TO_IURI.If the file name is "foo%2Fbar", the return value of getUnpackedValueOrDefault() will probably be "foo%252Fbar".Because the return value is url-encoded(percent-encoded).If we use DECODE_TO_IURI, decoded result will be "foo%252Fbar".If we use DECODE_WITH_CHARSET, decoded result will be "foo%2Fbar".

Patch Set 3:(1 comment)Thank you for your advice.I also think that the variable name "aDocumentName" is very misleading.1. About the insert point to decode URL.As you wrote, I think that the best way to convert is in PasswordDialog ctor.However, to reduce the influence I now was according to the method for the other formats(odf,etc...).For the other formats, probably insert points to decode URL are just before calling the UNO API, Document(MS)PasswordRequest(2). (e.g.   http://opengrok.libreoffice.org/xref/core/sfx2/source/appl/appopen.cxx#245  http://opengrok.libreoffice.org/xref/core/sw/source/filter/ww8/ww8par.cxx#5468)Somehow, those APIs want "the name of the document"... Therefore, in the case of OOXML, I think that the insert point to decode URL is either within MediaDescriptor::requestAndVerifyDocPassword() in unotools or DocPasswordHelper::requestAndVerifyDocPassword() in comphelper.Because the latter point has a smaller effect, I will modify the patch.(I think in the comphelper, INetURLObject can not be used because of the module dependencies. So, I will call directly rtl::url::decode().)2. About decodeMechanism for converting URL.I tried the two ways of rtl_UriDecodeWithCharset and rtl_UriDecodeToIuriRI, I have attached screen shots to bug report tdf#89694.https://bug-attachments.documentfoundation.org/attachment.cgi?id=113966https://bug-attachments.documentfoundation.org/attachment.cgi?id=113967I used this patch.https://bug-attachments.documentfoundation.org/attachment.cgi?id=113965I think the case in rtl_UriDecodeWithCharset is more user-friendly.If I mistake,  please point out.

Patch Set 1:This bug could be exhibiting multiple problems at higher levels, so I'm considering this fix to be a band-aid.  These problems are way above my expertise to comment on or investigate (see the bug report for background information.)1.)  I'd guess that adding support for some InsertObjectXXX toolbar functions registers a binding for a new textsh, which becomes dirty for every key press.  That seems expensive and buggy.  It is these "outside events" that are affecting the selection.2.)  I can't even guess at the circumstance that requires the popping of a cursor to cancel a selection.  Why is that code even in wrtsh1?  It seems to have been there since day1 and I have no idea how to identify whether it would be safe to remove it now.3.)  I hope there aren't any ÔÇ£necessary consequencesÔÇØ of calling push/pop that I've lost in bypassing them.  I think my proposed change is the least intrusive method of resolving this MAB quickly.4.)  I'm dancing around with cursorÔåÆHasMark(), shellÔåÆHasSelection() somewhere, and shellÔåÆIsSelection() with cursor presently in a selection.  Am I correct in equating HasSelection with HasMark?  Otherwise, the fix could be further limited to IsSelection.

Patch Set 1:Do we know the exact patchlevel that the parameters for CXXRecordDecl::forallBases were changed? If so, it may be better to use.    #if __clang_major__ == 3 && __clang_minor__ < 7 && __clang_patchlevel < xAs stated in the bug report I could be wrong here, but this is what I got to compile on my computer. Comments or constructive criticism are welcome!

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1(1 comment)> Do we know the exact patchlevel that the parameters for > CXXRecordDecl::forallBases were changed? If so, it may be better to > use. >  > #if __clang_major__ == 3 && __clang_minor__ < 7 && > __clang_patchlevel < x >  > As stated in the bug report I could be wrong here, but this is what > I got to compile on my computer. Comments or constructive criticism > are welcome!I routinely build the compilerplugins code against current builds of Clang trunk.  When there is breakage, I add #if blocks using the upcoming __clang_major/minor__ versions, but it may be the case that sometimes these breaking changes will not actually appear in that (then upcoming) version, but will only remain on trunk (towards the next version).  I have never yet seen it necessary to discriminate based on __clang_patchlevel.

Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2 Verified+1Ah the irony =) they're only disabled temporarily. I wanted to look at those guys and see if we can't improve them. We previously had tests that passed reliably =) I had hoped that eg. taking the median mark/space ratio between a few dozen AutoTimer triggers and comparing that to what it is supposed to be would show us whether we were spinning the mainloop hard rather than doing nice periodic updates eg.But I didn't read the unit test code too carefully - thanks so much for re-basing the cleanups =) lets submit as/when CI builds it cleanly if it can.

Patch Set 4:> Ah the irony =) they're only disabled temporarily. I wanted to look > at those guys and see if we can't improve them. We previously had > tests that passed reliably =)My tests are far more stringent than previous tests, AFAIK. > I had hoped that eg. taking the > median mark/space ratio between a few dozen AutoTimer triggers and > comparing that to what it is supposed to be would show us whether > we were spinning the mainloop hard rather than doing nice periodic > updates eg.That would work. The tests I wrote were counting the number of times the timers trigger in a multi-timer scenario. What I had discovered is that there is a lack of consistency, which I have plans to fix/address.For example, when two timers have the same timeout and priority, one could get a very low trigger rate (or none at all). This is because the trigger logic always picks the one with highest priority that is next in line, and so can end up picking the same timer to trigger every time, starving the other(s).I have a patch to address this and also to fix make IdleTimer fire only when the process idles. >  > But I didn't read the unit test code too carefully - thanks so much > for re-basing the cleanups =) lets submit as/when CI builds it > cleanly if it can.The reason I had disabled the fail condition when the new tests were excluded is because the remaining code is useful in detecting timers that don't trigger during the watchdog timeout. That is, timers should eventually trigger, even if they don't trigger with any accuracy. So I was effectively disabling the accuracy test, but the timers should've triggered during the dozen seconds that the watchdog ways (which you've increased). The test not passing reliably was because of the strictness of the precision tests, not the fact that timers weren't triggering (which would be a real bug). The precision tests are only meaningful if they come with some delta, and I had used 10-20%, increasing it would mean more passing runs, but less useful precision tests. Let's keep them disabled for now.Thanks again for the reviews and helping with this. And please expect more patches on timers.

Patch Set 1:> by the way "include-what-you-use" should report these as well, > although not in windows-only code yet because we'd need to be able > to build with clang on windows first. >  > see also easy-hack  https://bugs.documentfoundation.org/show_bug.cgi?id=42949Thanks Michael. Good to know. The reason I wrote this script is because I have another patch that improves pch generation (a rewrite of update_pch in python that updates every single pch in the codebase in a few seconds). It was obvious to me that to improve the pch generation to make builds faster I had to deal with the problem of conflicting headers (that are excluded from pch) and required headers (that will break the build if left out). This script solves the latter problem, so now what is included in pch headers is purely to accelerate builds, not to prevent the build from breaking.Will submit the update_pch script and updated pch files sometime soon, as time permits.

Patch Set 1:This patch needs a careful review by someone who understands how redlines and SPRMs work.  I don't understand this code - I just figured out something that fixed my problem and tried to make it as targeted as possible.  I'm not really sure of the implications - it just didn't seem to do anything bad to my sample document....  The biggest problem is that this is called at the end of EVERY cell, regardless of whether it is touching a redline. I couldn't figure out how to recognize when that occurs.	What I think is happening is that the WriteCR attribute from the PREVIOUS cell is being attached to the redline group and merged together.   However, although the IncludeEndOfParaCRInRedlineProperties() method seems to try to handle these things, it isn't catching this case.	How to write a automated compile testcase for this fix is beyond me since I don't understand what is happening deep in the code, and I can only see the problem when looking at the document in Word.  Several manual testcases are attached to the bug report.

Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1OK - false alarm.  Sorry - I'm making false connections in my mind about what the old code actually did, and all of the situations it messed up.  The old code DID only handle increasing sequential links - just sometimes it ran across the bigger one first, and then matched with the first higher/lower one that it came across.  It was MY example that actually was numbered in the reverse order and so wouldn't have worked on the old logic.  OK - shouldn't be a regression after-all.  And your test document loaded/looked fine.

Patch Set 6:OK - false alarm.  Sorry - I'm making false connections in my mind about what the old code actually did, and all of the situations it messed up.  The old code DID only handle increasing sequential links - just sometimes it ran across the bigger sequence first, and then reversed the logic to matched with the lower one.  It was MY example doc (albeit vml) that actually was numbered in the reverse order and so wouldn't have worked on the old logic. And your test document loaded/looked fine.  So in my mind I'm combining all that plus some things I saw (can't remember all where) about mso-layout-flow-alt indicating a reverse sequence - where the highest number starts the chain instead of ends the chain, but although this alt-flow is put in the grabbag, it is never used.  In the end the lack of reverse chaining is still a (potentially) missing feature, not a regression.

Do you see the text "<slide-name>" at a different place than is style:master-page? (I have no build to look myself.) Besides that, the actual slide name need not be of the kind "Slide 1" but can be any user-defined string.

Patch Set 2:> thanks for working on this; it's looking fine; > the only issue is that the commit does add 2 new en-US strings It does, I'm well aware of that, also of the fact that the strings aren't going to be translated. However, they're only used as placeholders for export (and in master view, but come on, how many users will see them there?)   > the feature as currently implemented should not be in the 4.4 > release, > inserting fields that cannot be stored is utterly pointlessIt is. Some LibO hackers with commit rights sometimes go around and merge patches to the code they have almost no clue about. And then other LibO hackers advertise such half-baked features in release notes. > - but adding new strings is not allowed now, not sure > what to do?  can the new strings be avoided for 4.4? Either use English strings directly in C++ code (but that doesn't change the user experience, there will English strings either way), or see below: > also when i try it i get this in the file: >  > <loext:page-name><slide-name></loext:page-name> >  > i think the field text should be the same as in the document > display, i.e. the character content should be "Slide 1"<slide-name> is a placeholder and it'll be substituted by real slide name after import, during rendering. I've looked at what other fields do and some (e.g. page number SvxPageField) don't save the real content of the field either, but use a placeholder. So I did the same.For this particular 4.4 backport, we could maybe save the slide name as character content. That would nicely bypass the problem of new (and untranslated) English strings

Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1The import part looks good, and functions very well.  Great job on doing your analysis and coming up with a very well thought-out solution.Now, the only remaining issue is the saving.  Right now, when you open a csv.gz file, edits it, and hits Ctrl-S, it saves it back to the file uncompressed, while the extension is intact.  This is not ideal.I can think of 2 ways to resolve this.  The first way is to support saving it back gz compressed, by somehow storing the information that this file has been uncompressed and using that information and trigger gz compression on saving.  In this scenario, you need to be careful not to compress on save when the user decides to save the file with a different name.  There would be other corner cases you'd have to handle when going this route. Personally I don't like this solution.The 2nd way is to load the file read only when the file is automatically uncompressed during file detection.  This way, when the user wants to edit it and re-save it, she won't be able to overwrite the original file.  I personally like this solution.Here is the gotcha, though.  Forcing a read-only load is as easy as setting the read only flag to true with the media descriptor, which will prompt you that the document has been opened read only, and to edit it, the user will need to click "Edit document" to create a new document instance.  When you do that, Calc will still load the compressed stream into the 2nd document instance, not the uncompressed version.  This needs to be addressed.I hope this will not be too much trouble to solve.  Good luck!

Patch Set 8:Great analysis!  I personally think that (assuming that it works) your approach 3) is the best approach under the circumstance.  Could you make the change for that and update your patch?  I'd like to give that a spin.One very minor thing I would change is to switch from replaceFirst() to copy() to get a substring of the original URL in order to remove the .gz extension.  Using replaceFirst is fine, but I personally find using the copy() method more "natural" for that sort of use given that you already have the position of the ".gz" string.  You can use nIdx as the "length" of the new substring when using copy().Thanks a lot!

Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1This patch still has issues.1) The new option shouldn't be added to the popup window since it's not an action but it's an attribute. The popup window is the wrong place to house this option.  It should go to the Field options dialog which can be reached from the layout dialog by double-clicking on the field name (which is kinda hidden, I know).  Once that dialog is open, you still need to click on the Options button to get to the actual dialog where you need to add this option.2) This should be a field (or dimension as it's called in the code) option. As such, it should be stored in ScDPSaveDimension as a new boolean member, not in ScDPSaveData, which should only store table-wide options.3) ODF export code should also reflect that, and store the new setting as a dimension attribute.  Right now you are saving it as a table attribute, which is wrong.  I didn't check your change in the import code, but I'd guess it has a similar issue.I did check Excel once again. Excel doesn't offer this as a table wide option. Only a field setting option.  What you saw is probably the print option where the user can choose to repeat field names when printing. But that's an entirely different setting.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1The patch looks completely reasonable from the POV of the current state of the code. However, code archaeology suggests that merge commit 67d2af6fac2d9bad52a6b1f6e0cbd1229eb88a42 erroneously removed the call to "ImplUpdate" in MoveItem, since that line is present in BOTH parents of that merge. The "if ( nNewPos < nPos )" seems to be done for the sake of the ImplUpdate, to set the argument it will be called with. It looks reasonable, since the call is made with the default value of bDirect==false, then ImplUpdate updates *all* columns after its first argument (its argument inclusive). So it is essentially called with ::std::min(nPos, nNewPos).So it seems to me that we should rather fix the error in bd24a310be1459510b760b812838cb87923853c5 of using "nPos" instead of "nNewPos" in the second call of ::std::advance (the one before insert), but leave the "if ( nNewPos < nPos )" and reinsert the "ImplUpdate(nPos, ...)".Kendy, I know it is far away, but would you agree with my analysis of your merge commit?Julien, could you try out my suggestion above and test its effects, if the behaviour is good, the bug is still fixed, no other obvious bug is introduced, etc? Thanks in advance.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1The basic idea is a good one here. Clearly the ScHorizontalAttrIter is used in a ton of places across the code-base, particularly in filters, and making it ~instant for all the common big-data cases is very helpful.The basic approach looks good too - the nMinNextEnd looks sensible to detect large runs of identical formatting.What doesn't convince me that much is the initialization and management of the pPrevColEnd array. It looks like that is not initialized initially [sic] ;-) and then there is an assumption that:                if ( bRepeatedRow )                    nCol = pPrevColEnd[nCol];-but- (AFAICS) there is no guarentee that pPrevColEnd[nCol] is setup correctly - it rather depends on the value of nCol that was used last time - which (in turn) depends on the shape of the data.So - I would suggest adopting a different approach for generating and managing that - along with some nicer data structure for this case. IIWY I'd detect the case where there is a large run of identical styles - and in that case do more work to analyze them into a complete structure - that can be re-used for several subsequent rows; eg. if there are > 2x rows with the same thing - then allocate & fill that structure in (eg.).Is that do-able ? hopefully it'll make the code flow more pleasant too =)I'd also like to see a unit test created for the case that looks like it should fail in the above =) where we have constant patterns down a run - but a random layout of cell content.Thanks !

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1Calling maItemList.erase(it) indeed invalidates it, we are not authorised to use it any more.However, assigning to it the return value of erase does not match my understanding of the code block that follows the for loop, that is issue a SAL_WARN if the button id to be deleted was not found. Now this SAL_WARN would incorrectly be triggered when the last button (the one that is last in maItemList) is successfully deleted.At first I thought about: * introducing a boolean flag "found" for this information,   which is a bit awkward, especially for an information that   is used only in debug mode:   bool found(false);   for(...)   {       if(...)       {           found=true;           ....       }   }   if(!found)       SAL_WARN(...) * taking more control of the looping than in a "usual" for loop pattern:   for (it = maItemList.begin(); ; ++it)   {       if (it == maItemList.end())       {           SAL_WARN( "vcl.window", "ButtonDialog::RemoveButton(): ButtonId invalid" );           break;       }       else if (it->mnId == nId)       {           ...       }   }but then I got the idea of just replacing the "break" by a "return" since this is the end of the function anyway.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1(3 comments)i'm a bit confused here....do we need to export only the top level element table:table in a different namespace?it looks like you want to export table-row / table-column / cell in different namespace too and forgot covered-cell.but why change the namespace of these 3-4 elements and not the paragraphs contained in the cells etc. etc.?changing the namespace of everything inside the table is going to be quite painful, isn't it enough to only change the top-level table element?

Patch Set 1:Hi,> do we need to export only the top level element table:table in a different namespace?Just table:table is not enough, as you see in the patch, all the table-related elements have to be in the extension namespace, odfvalidator says so at least.> it looks like you want to export table-row / table-column / cell in different namespace too and forgot covered-cell.Indeed, I'll fix covered-cell.> but why change the namespace of these 3-4 elements and not the paragraphs contained in the cells etc. etc.?The idea is that table-in-shape is a new feature, but text-in-shape is not, so if a reader is not capable of table-in-shape, it can still import the text of the table into the shape. (Slightly related example: old RTF import did the same for nested tables.)> changing the namespace of everything inside the table is going to be quite painful, isn't it enough to only change the top-level table element?I needed the minimal changes to make odfvalidator happy. That means changing the prefix of table:*, but not the content of the tables, which would be indeed painful.I'll fix the rest on master and upload a new revision.

Patch Set 1:Sorry this took so long.  (I had had a quick look at the patch, which looks more complicated on first sight than it actually is, due to the necessary changes to indentation, but then lost sight of it again.)getAllJREInfos (jvmfwk/plugins/sunmajor/pluginlib/util.cxx, called indirectly from jfw_findAndSelectJRE via jfw_plugin_getAllJavaInfos) already searches JAVA_HOME and PATH for JREs, they just don't get priority treatment in the current jfw_findAndSelectJRE.  It would probably be better to not have that search code also in jfw_findAndSelectJRE, but rather transport the information about how a JRE has been found from getAllJREInfos to jfw_findAndSelectJRE, so that the latter can pick the "best" based on that and not only on version numbers.(Also, the plugin architecture in jvmfwk is probably over-architectured, and I would like to get rid of it, not the least to drop all the #ifdef DISABLE_DYNLOADINGs, and to ease maintenance of that code.)

Patch Set 1:Thank you very much for your feedback and your hints!I have thought about how to best implement this and would appreciate your feedback on my ideas.The possibilities I am currently thinking about are as follows:1) Add two new functions (e.g. "jfw_plugin_getJavaInfoFromJavaHome", "jfw_plugin_getJavaInfosFromPath") to vendorplugin.hxx and sunjavaplugin.cxx to obtain information about Java installations referred to by JAVA_HOME and PATH environment variables (similar to jfw_plugin_getAllJavaInfos). The two functions use the functions in util.cxx to get the information.jfw_findAndSelectJRE uses the two new functions to check for such Java installations and uses them if there are any, otherwise uses the algorithm that is currently used.This would avoid duplicate code in jfw_findAndSelectJRE and getAllJREInfos.2) Add additional (out) parameters to getAllJREInfos and jfw_plugin_getAllJavaInfos that hold the JavaInfos that have been found using JAVA_HOME or PATH.possible new signature:javaPluginError jfw_plugin_getAllJavaInfos(    rtl_uString *sVendor,    rtl_uString *sMinVersion,    rtl_uString *sMaxVersion,    rtl_uString * * arExcludeList,    sal_Int32  nSizeExcludeList,    JavaInfo*** parJavaInfo,    sal_Int32 *nSizeJavaInfo,    JavaInfo** parJavaInfoFromJavaHome,    JavaInfo*** parJavaInfosFromPath,    sal_Int32 *nSizeJavaInfosFromPath);If JAVA_HOME points to a suitable Java installation, parJavaInfoFromJavaHome points to it.If suitable Java installations are on the PATH, parJavaInfosFromPath holds the respective JavaInfos and nSizeJavaInfosFromPath is the number of JavaInfos found on the PATH.The additional parameters would be unused for "normal" calls to the method and only be used in jfw_findAndSelectJRE (which is possibly no good design?).3) Add an additional field to the _JavaInfo struct that tells how the Java installation has been found. I currently don't have a reasonable idea how to actually implement that field - which should be able to tell e.g. that the Java installation is referred to by JAVA_HOME, and/or is the 1st Java on the PATH, the 2nd Java on the PATH,..., or has been found in a different way.As far as I understand, the struct is defined in include/jvmfwk/framework.h and the new field would thus also be visible from outside the "jvmfwk" module.I personally consider solution 1) to be the best of those three, but would appreciate your feedback. Of course, a totally different solution is welcome, too.

Patch Set 3:When designing the framework, we had two basic ideas:- interesting document models are easier to be loaded from some format, than building them from code- checking an in-memory document model is reasonably easy (usually by using the UNO API), at least easier than asserting a written file (think of manually checking a binary .doc result)That's why for export tests, we do an import->export->import sequence. That ensures that the doc. models can be still stored in a file, allows asserting the result using the UNO API, and still export problems are detected. (I'm just re-stating what's in sw/qa/extras/README, just in case for some reason that file is not clear.) Hopefully this makes it clear how export tests are done. :-)Regarding loosing data during import/export: sure, sometimes that's necessary when e.g. our numbering types and MSO's numbering types do not match. In your case, the provided tests passed just fine when also the exporter got included in the chain, that's why I changed that. As long as it passes, it's safe to change, and it ensures that your export improvements won't break in the future silently. ;-)

Patch Set 1:Hi,Once you're ready with your inline comments, you can just push the reply + send button (without filling the textarea), and then your comments will be published.About numeric tokens: would it be possible to adjust rtftok to emit the necessary NS_ooxml::LN_something tokens instead? The idea is that RTF is a no longer developed format, while OOXML still introduces new features, so RTF is a subset of OOXML. Based on that, dmapper should in general handle OOXML, and rtftok should just emit those ooxml tokens, not its own ones. So there should be as minimal RTF-specific code in dmapper as possible.About unit tests, see here for documentation: http://opengrok.libreoffice.org/xref/core/sw/qa/extras/READMEOne RTF, one DOC and one DOCX export test would be the optimal.Thanks! :-)

Patch Set 1:Thanks for the hint. Obviously I need to learn more about git and gerrit, I had a hard time finding out how to back-port a change at all. Do you want me to abandon this change and redo it with git cherry-pick -x? Or just modify the message?One more question, If I do "git cherry-pick -x", should the hash after be the Change-Id or the commit-id. Also I need to have the libreoffice4-3 branch checked-out before I do the git cherry-pick -x, right?Sorry if these are stupid questions, but I've had a hard time finding good info on how to do this.

Patch Set 1:No no, your questions are fully reasonable! You switch to the 4-3 branch and do git cherry-pick -x commit-id there. The commit-id of your commit in the master branch is unique inside the whole git tree. So this works this easy.You don't need to abandon this change. If your new patch has the same "Change-Id" as this one gerrit will notice it as second version of this patchset. So you do git cherry-pick -x and after that change the "Change-Id" to Ibd04cf5329b4d226aac102d214a45e45811982e7 . That should be enough :)

Patch Set 1:Parsing looks fine; the output side is not working at all, however.The issue is that Pagemaker and LibreOffice use two different forms for representing an ellipse. Pagemaker uses bounds, skew, and rotation; LibreOffice uses center, length of x axis, length of y axis, and rotation.Before we can write the code, we need to figure out how to translate from one form into the other. Once we figure out that formula, writing the code should be easy.I'm pretty sure the last time I thought about ellipses was in school a decade or so ago, so I'm not sure exactly how to do this. I can spend some time tomorrow thinking about it. I think it's probably very standard; I just need to find it documented in a geometry book somewhere or figure it out myself :)If you upload the parsing piece as a separate patch, we can merge it in now, since it appears to work.

Patch Set 2:OK, Pasting from Impress overwrites, you mean. Or are there some overwritten when pasting from writer? The catch is that I do not know how to change a object's positioning info. It simply does not work. But I need that in order to preserve the overwrite-into-frame functionality when I introduce a new menu Item, otherwise THAT would be confusing.

Patch Set 2:First, thanks for working on this.I am sorry, I could not test the patch easily because I do not longer work on LO and do not have the build environment at hands. So, I just react to the comments.If this patch causes that Draw behaves different way when pasting from Writer and Draw then it is even less intuitive that the previous behavior and I suggest to revert it.IMHO, it should not matter where you paste from. Also all LO appications should handle the pasting the same way.When I think about it, the confusion might be in the definition of selected object. If you select part of text in Writer and paste something, the selected text is overwritten, so writer behaves the same way as Draw.The problem is that in Writer, if no test is selected, the cursor is somewhere between two characters and pasted text is added. No text is selected most of the time when you write a text. You need to do explict action (select the text) to overwrite it.In draw, the last added or edited object is always selected, so most of the time some object is selected. This causes that the last object is overwritten when pasting. You need to do explicit action (deselect the object) to avoid overwriting.To be honest I am not sure how to solve this.PS: I am sorry if I added the comment a wrong way. I am not familiar with the current Gerrint interface. I did not find any way how to replay any existing comment.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1Thank you for the patch!  I wonder - do we have to introduce a new flag?  Isn't it enough to re-use the GETFOCUS_TAB here too?Also about removing if(GETFOCUS_TAB & GetGetFocusFlags()) - what now happens when you click there; won't it lead to extra focusing and unfocusing?  Or is that unrelated?The rest is nitpicking :-) - if we really need GETFOCUS_F6, it should be 0x0800, not 0x1000.  PreNotify() should return true's, not 1's.Thanks so much - and sorry the review took so long; -1's for now, hope that's OK, please set back to 0 when you upload a new patch at some stage.

Patch Set 3:Hi Kendy,> I wonder - do we have to introduce a new flag?Of course. In some case it is useful to differentiate focusing caused by F6 or TAB. e.g. in BackingWindow::GetFocus(), GETFOCUS_F6 + !GETFOCUS_FORWARD -> grab focus to thumbnailview while GETFOCUS_TAB -> nothing> Also about removing if(GETFOCUS_TAB & GetGetFocusFlags()) - what now happens when you click there; won't it lead to extra focusing and unfocusing? Or is that unrelated?Yes, you are right. I will revert this change and will add a more explicit solution which will select item just when it is actually necessary. Unfortunately ImplGrabFocus() can't be used outside vcl, which would be a simple way (e.g. using ImplGrabFocus(GETFOCUS_F6) inside BackingWindow too).> The rest is nitpicking :-) - if we really need GETFOCUS_F6, it should be 0x0800, not 0x1000.Are you sure? I just look these GETFOCUS_ flags are defined in this way leaving out 0x0008, 0x0080 and I thought maybe somewhere these flags are used in a special way (e.g. some special bit operation) which makes it necessary.> PreNotify() should return true's, not 1's.Oh, yes. This is the result of new bool improvements. :)

Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approveSo - in general in-lining headers like this is fine - assuming that we are just moving these redundant extra headers into others that are included anyway.However - looking at the number counts we do more than this:0       65      slideshow/source/inc/animationfunction.hxx104     6       slideshow/source/inc/eventmultiplexer.hxx28      2       slideshow/source/inc/expressionnode.hxx176     2       slideshow/source/inc/listenercontainer.hxx30      1       slideshow/source/inc/shapeattributelayer.hxx0       61      slideshow/source/inc/shapecursoreventhandler.hxx0       67      slideshow/source/inc/state.hxx0       59      slideshow/source/inc/userpainteventhandler.hxx0       67      slideshow/source/inc/viewrepainthandler.hxxSo - a lot more code ends up in the new headers than is removed from the old ones: where does that come from ?I'm very scared by things like:+class MutexBase+{+public:+    struct Guard : public osl::MutexGuard+    {+        explicit Guard(MutexBase const& rBase) :+            osl::MutexGuard(rBase.maMutex)+        {}+    };+    struct ClearableGuard : public osl::ClearableMutexGuard+    {+        explicit ClearableGuard(MutexBase const& rBase) :+            osl::ClearableMutexGuard(rBase.maMutex)+        {}+    };++    mutable osl::Mutex maMutex;+};Then I noticed that you just forgot to git rm 'listenercontainerimpl.hxx' that has this stuff in it.Quite why we have this 'MutexBase' class I have no idea it looks odd to me - but that's a problem for another commit =)So - anyhow - this is good. There is really not a lot of value using a pimpl pattern for classes that are internal to slideshow anyway, so - this inlining seems rather helpful.Thanks ! will push in a sec.

Patch Set 2:Hmmm - the problem is, when loading such a document, the strings getmatched against existing table styles, and then the table design paneselects the right icon for the currently-selected table object.Now, if you change the name, when loading an old doc, Impress willon-demand create a new style (since the name 'turquise' is unknown),and assign a matching icon. So you'll end up with a bunch of dupeentries in that widget.I wonder if this rather cosmetic change is worth that user annoyance?Alternatively, one could of course map the names on import, doubtfulthough if that's worth the hassle ...

Patch Set 2: Verified; Looks good to me, approvedso it looks like we actually write the name of these table styles into the ODF file...... as table:template-name="turquise" on table:table element.this means that the values will be read from the ODF file anyway so it shouldn't matter what the styles are called internally (that will just affect new files).the only problem i can see is that if you load a document with the old spelling you can see an additional entry in "Table Design" but i think it's not really a problem.

Patch Set 6: Verified; Looks good to me, approvedIn case I insert a page at the end of a new doc (numbered "1", physically 3 out of 3), the toolbar says "Page 1 3/3". (No idea why not "Page 1 2/2".) In this zero case, it says "Page 0/4", which is a bit confusing.OTOH I guess it improves the current situation, so let's get it in.Oh, and one more thing: in SwLayHelper::CheckInsertPage(), it's not trivial why you check the page number of the *follow* style. It would be great to have a follow-up commit that adds a comment, explaining that.

Patch Set 3:> vmiklos: I have updated all the relevant places to now use 'optional'.Great, thanks!> In 'sw/source/ui/utlui/uitool.cxx' the 'SfxUInt16Item aPageNum' is set in the function 'SwToSfxPageDescAttr'. Question is - now that 'GetNumOffset' *could* return NULL - what should be done if it *is* null ? should we set '0' to the 'SfxUInt16Item' (like I've done) ?If we're speaking about SwToSfxPageDescAttr(), what about just not putting the SfxPoolItem to the item set? Of course, then the consumer of that item set (insert->manual break dialog?) should handle the lack of the pool item in the set, but I guess that's logical: item missing -> "change page number" checkbox is false, item there -> "change page number" checkbox is true and the value can be even 0, if you need it.> In 'sw/source/ui/table/tabledlg.cxx' the code *used* to set the 'NumericField' with the value from the 'GetNumOffset()' function, but now it returns an optional value. so if the value is NULL - should it *not* set the NumericValue or it *should* set it, but with 0 (like I've done) ?This is the UI I was mentioning above. :) I guess null should be "checkbox false, numeric field empty", while 0 should be "checbox true, numeric field 0". Hopefully that's intuitive enough.

Important bits are Gallery.mk and CppunitTest.mk, where 'xcsxcu' in CONFIGURATION_LAYERS is changed and 'module' is no more used.I hope something like this is possible.. patches to remove $(OUTDIR)/xml are almost done ;-)btw: 'xcsxcu' and 'res' in CONFIGURATION_LAYERS in instsetoo_native/CustomTarget_setup.mk have the same value, is it right ?Otherwise only 'xcsxcu' is now used AFAICS, so possibly also configmgr can be simplified ?

Patch Set 1:"Sorry, that the patch is big. Important bits are Gallery.mk and CppunitTest.mk, where 'xcsxcu' in CONFIGURATION_LAYERS is changed and 'module' is no more used. I hope something like this is possible.. patches to remove $(OUTDIR)/xml are almost done ;-)"That would mean that the affected modules would now (circularly, at the module level) depend on postprocess, right?  (Not that is necessarily a bad thing to introduce such "false" module-level circular dependencies.)"btw: 'xcsxcu' and 'res' in CONFIGURATION_LAYERS in instsetoo_native/CustomTarget_setup.mk have the same value, is it right ? Otherwise only 'xcsxcu' is now used AFAICS, so possibly also configmgr can be simplified ?"Each of "xcsxcu", "res", and "module" parse slightly different sets of files, cf. configmgr/source/components.cxx.  What you loose with the changes to CppunitTest.mk is to read the localized instdir/*/share/registry/res/*.xcd files, which also include the fallback *-en_US.xcd ones, which might or might not be a problem for (some of) the tests.  But if it turns out to be a problem, we could easily add that afterwards.

Patch Set 1:"That would mean that the affected modules would now (circularly, at the module level) depend on postprocess, right?"Right. (only on a part of postprocess.)It's a feature of gbuild. Not ideal in general, but in this case I think it's worthy.It's a bit sad we lost module dependencies, but at least there is something based on libraries.

Patch Set 5: This need some tweaks before it is mergedAlso here some more explanation would be great, as this is not iOS-only code, but cross-platform.So the commit comment is a bit misleading, too.

Patch Set 5: This need some tweaks before it is mergedHmm. So there's already a check for a straight copy, now delegating to vigra::copyImage, in scaleimage.hxx. Then again, that one will still see e.g. XOR accessors, so it's indeed not the ideal place to stick this.I wonder though, are those 'longs' really idiomatic? The incoming data types have exact sizes, and I'm not against int for loop counters, but long?

Patch Set 5:The vigra::copyImage is not handling copy areas in the same image so the code is checking whether the src and dst are same buffer and directing it to scaleImage which is very slow.The whole concept of pixel accessors is a huge overhead in the case of direct pixel copy (vigra::copyImage is also using pixel accessors).The idea here was to identify when direct memory copy is applicable (when src.size==dst.size && src.format==dst.format) and use direct memory block copy and not pixel wise copy.The result is 100x faster than vigra implementation.This direct copy is also handling the case when the src and dst are same buffer by copy it from bottom to top when needed and using memmove instead of memcpyabout using long or int for iterating i'm not keen on the cross platform details please advice how to do it properly.

Patch Set 5:Yep, no beef with the function per se - my verbose comment was more a documentation of why this is a good idea. ;)For the variables - please double-check this, but from the math, sal_Int32 should be sufficient. This is on all of our platforms interchangeable with int, so why not use that.If the original intend of long was 'something bigger than int', then you should use sal_Int64 (I doubt it is needed though).

Patch Set 1: Verified; Looks good to me, but someone else must approveMikl├│s, thanks for your review. The simplicity of the patch is conscious. Using the character sequence "\t" is an artificial problem in footnote numbering, but you can specify it using standard Unicode methods, adding a zero width non joiner between "\" and "t" (U+200C).This patch fixes a real problem (*bug of the user interface* distorts the document, prohibits the stable work of a fine workaround for a long-term problem). It is not the *ideal* solution, but there were more than 10 years to fix the original problem, the missing right aligned footnote numbering, without any known result (only my Graphite solution with Linux Libertine G and Biolinum G a few years ago). I was very glad to find a general workaround not depending my particular font enhancements a few days ago, fixing it with this patch, but if you will be able to fix the original problem in a more proper way (eg. adding a check box for right alignment) for LibreOffice 4.1, I won't want to force this patch. This is only a temporary UI fix to keep stable document format. More about this problem (in Hungarian): http://libreoffice.hu/2013/06/13/jobbra-zart-labjegyzetszamozas/Thanks again. Laci

Patch Set 1: Verified; Looks good to me, approvedThe root of the problem, that vcl's Edit control does not handle TAB character for some reason. Maybe it makes sense, maybe not. This patch can be accepted as a temporary solution to the specific problem. Of course "temporary" may mean yet another 10 years. :) I'll extend the help to document this great improvement.

Patch Set 4:I am not really happy about the commit message. Reading it, it is hard to understand what effect the patch actually has. Please don't use passive voice. Write simple, imperative statements describing what effect the patch has.If you need to refer to the behaviour of code before the patch, be explicit, as in "Foo previously did bar", not "The way it works now". (Saying how something works "now" is ambiguous, does it mean "now, after this patch" or "now, before this patch".)Instead of "saving to docx is fixed", say "fix saving to docx". (But does the patch really fix saving to docx in general, was that broken? Or do you mean compared to a previous version of the patch? In that case, no need to mention it, once this goes into git, any iterations ("patch sets") it had in gerrit is irrelevant.
Patch Set 4:Sure. And sorry for nitpicking about the commit message...

Patch Set 1:This patch fixed the conditional style handling of tables if importing docx files. As described in: http://social.msdn.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/os_openXML-ecma/thread/1febafab-67d7-4a26-ac51-fec69a39c2fe/The cnfStyle doesn't have a function and should not be used to determine the table style, instead the tblLook property has to be used.I fixed this, I added a bugdoc that contains a table without cnfStyle Properties, this file looks bad in LO, but good in Word.As a side effect, now also the table corner styles are imported properly.Best regards,Sven

Patch Set 2:> I think the two load options should be set to not expand vertically, looks a bit silly.The reason I did it this way was because otherwise the width of the combo box would change dynamically depending on the current selection, and I wanted to avoid that. I guess I could have set the width to a fixed value, but I wanted the GUI toolkit to do the sizing, feels more flexible.> The warning could go under the dropdown that it applies to now that nothing has to be manually moved in the code.I put it in the end because it was there in the original code, and because otherwise I would have to leave an empty row there, or have everything under it move down when it appears. I thought I should try to keep all the GUI elements static, and not jump around when a user changes something, to avoid confusion.> odfwarning never seems to appear but maybe that's a wider/theme bugIt did appear for me under Linux Mint 14 MATE, what OS are you on?

Patch Set 4:Thanks for your review.As far I tested, there is no need to distinguish the Footnotes from the Footers. This because the Footnotes are stored before the Footers, so the anchors are determined correctly. The only thing I improved in this patch is to check the anchor is placed in Footer or Footnote (by FindFootnoteStartNode() and FindFooterStartNode(). If this isn't the right way, please feel free to say so, but it works (please also see my test document in the commit comment and bug report).Kind regards,Joren

Patch Set 1: Do not mergeHi there - thanks so much for this work; I assume you used a script for this ? :-) if so it's prolly better to discuss / review the script.A couple of things - the newly introduced trialing newlines at the end of files may cause some grief so prolly best to drop those. Otherwise the only issue I saw was of these horrible UTF-8 pre-characters; cf:--- a/xmlsecurity/source/dialogs/macrosecurity.src+++ b/xmlsecurity/source/dialogs/macrosecurity.src@@ -1,3 +1,4 @@+/* -*- Mode: C++; tab-width: 4; indent-tabs-mode: nil; c-basic-offset: 4 -*- */ <U+FEFF>/*That U+FEFF is a double-byte character that goes as the first char; and (in this case) we now have it in the middle of the file ;-) If you're using a perl-script something like this:    while (<$in>) {	my $line = $_;	# we sometimes get some mis-guided utf-8 flagging chars at the top	if ($line_count == 0 && defined ($fmt->{bin_utf8})) {	    $line =~ s/^\xef\xbb\xbf//;	}will detect & fix that up I guess. Inspired by:http://cgit.freedesktop.org/libreoffice/contrib/dev-tools/tree/scripts/headerize.plAnyhow - thanks again for working on this - it'd be great to get your change in with those things tweaked !

Patch Set 1:yes finding those methods is hard, really sometimes given the size of the code its a case of a) someone tells you or b) you come across it while looking at the issue you are trying to fix or c) you came across the code previously ( and managed to remember it )you are doing a great job in anycase, don't dispair, calc is tough nut to crack and you seem to be managing fine. Patch Set 1:Thanks for your supportive message.I try to concentrate on calc and so be able to use what I found out earlier (if indeed I could only remember it).The intersect-check has been changed and works fine, the FindAreaPos is a dead-end (if that's proper English). It stops at hidden columns/rows and continues until it finds a non-empty cell. Imagine a sheet with some data in row 1 and some in row 2 and you wanting to cut row 2 and paste+shift down above row 1. FindAreaPos will check (MAXROW-2)*MAXCOL cells, where only MAXCOL cells need to be checked. But I started looking around in the code and found ScDocument::IsEmptyBlock() and that looks promising. Still building though (slow machine at my work) and I want to test it before submitting the new patch set.

Patch Set 1: Verified; Looks good to me, approvedGreat, code converted correctly. Some small nits...ObjectNameDialog:  - Lets make dialogs resizeable unless there's a reason not to. The old ones weren't resizeable because of the lack-of-layout defect.   - some pixel size-requests on edit-boxes, maybe worried about its default size? So I set a "width in chars" on the edit box to make it wide enough, that way we don't have to worry about measuring things in pixelsObjectTitleNameDialog   - Lets make it resizeable, as above.  - The original had a scrollbar, so added a scrolledwindow to it with always vertically scroll  - For the textview to give it a default height, rather than using pixels I let it take its width by expand to the above edit widget width  - For its height, added a non-translated text buffer with 5 blank lines and tweaked the ctor to set that as its permanent height request  - GtkTextView maps to class VclMultiLineEdit instead of MultiLineEdit. This is a sort of bizarre impossible to know about corner case. But they should be equivalent, so I just changed MultiLineEdit to VclMultiLineEditNameDialog:  - width requests as above  - set name_entry as the mnemonic widget of name_entryMessBox:  - I set the label to be vertically centered for the resizeable caseI've been keeping things as one dialog per .ui file, which as a side effect allows no name collisions between various "ok" buttons being called "ok", etc, so I split them up like that.

Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit thisHmm, I am not sure that I like this change. It does not create the formatting entry without any explanation. You were able to edit the unused formatting and add the range later in the past.For example, imagine that you define some formatting, forget to define the range, and press the "Add" button. You will not know why the entry was not created. You will need to select everything again and again until you find why it does not work :-)IMHO, the best solution would be to preffil the range with the current selected cell(s). For example, the DataPilot or Chart is created from the current selection by default as well.Hmm, the prefil would be annoying if you lose some older formatting  in the selected cells. In this case, I would prefer to leave the behavior as is and fix it with the error dialog for 4.1. IMHO, the behavior is more annoying with the patch than without it.BTW: I really like the conditional formatting. It is very cool and useful feature. Thanks a lot for the hard work in this area.

Patch Set 1:Wouldn't it be better to keep throwing a PropertyVetoException from setSize, but let setHeight/Width translate that into a WrappedTargetRuntimeException?  That way, other clients of setSize would not be affected.Also, constructing an instance of Reference<XInterface> from *this confuses me -- not sure why it works here and if all compilers will accept it.  The standard idiom there is static_cast<cppu::OWeakObject*>(this).

Patch Set 2:> Wouldn't it be better to keep throwing a PropertyVetoException from setSizeYes, fair point. Corrected that.> but let setHeight/Width translate that into a WrappedTargetRuntimeException?No, throwing a WrappedTargetRuntimeException still leads to a crash.> Also, constructing an instance of Reference<XInterface> from *this confuses me -- not sure why it works here and if all compilers will accept it. The standard idiom there is static_cast<cppu::OWeakObject*>(this).Other places in the code definitely do it from *this, but indeed far fewer than with the static_cast<cppu::OWeakObject*>. I must have seen only the "bad" examples before...

Patch Set 1:"The whole check appears to be rather pointless. Do we actually use the result anywhere?"While we don't appear to be using HAVE_BOOST_UNORDERED_MAP anywhere (so setting it could be removed), we do #include "boost/unordered_map.hxx" in lots of places.  So if the system boost does not support that, we should probably error-out/switch to our boost.Forcing -std=gnu++0x for the check without coordinating that with HAVE_CXX0X (which will determine whether --std=gnu++0x is actually enabled in the build) is not really helpful, though.

Patch Set 1:Called functions: probably setFloat / setDouble / setInt / setLong / ... or updateFloat / updateDouble / updateInt / updateLong / ...From the point of view of the driver, it should provide all of those, and the calling code chooses which one to call. Calling code can not only be LibreOffice C++ code, but also user macros, so it cannot be predicted what choice is made.When you create a table and select a DECIMAL or NUMERIC field type, don't you have the following field properties, including "Decimal places"?Entry requires: Length: Decimal places:Default value:Format example:The rounding may be because the driver tells the rest of LibreOffice that 0 decimal places are allowed. Or it may be in the configuration of the UI element. Create a form, and edit the properties of the form control: do you use a formatted field or a numeric field? In a numeric field you can set the decimal accuracy. Check what is put there.When all else fails, I single-step in a debugger from the control's "write to the database calls" into the different layers. But that is a bit heavy-weight :)

Patch Set 1:Wrt. the starvation - actually that was due to the logging; we have so much debugging stuff that it was blocking considerably when writing to the console, making the queue grow.  Without that, all works fine even with the unmodified TileQueue :-)But I worked on the TileQueue too - it seems unnecessary to do all the priority shuffling when inserting, when the prioritization changes with every view switch, and instead do it only when the tile is requested - which seems to work nicely.Wrt. an own queue for tiles - that is exactly the thing that makes the synchronzation hard, as then it is necessary to synchronize between those 2 queues; which in turn kills all the advantage of 2 queues :-)Wrt. PNG compression; if we want to thread it, then let's thread just the compression - that'll make it local, more maintainable, and we can go with as many threads there as we wish (for just the PNG compression piece of code).Wrt. the 342125b8ea - thanks for that!  Unfortunately that again just adds code :-(Either way, please check https://cgit.freedesktop.org/libreoffice/online/log/?h=private/kendy/tilesandcallbacks , I'd really like to get that in...  I've tested it with several people in a session, and it performed pretty well thanks to all your work I was able to build on.
